📦 Core Icon Categories

    apps

        What it is: Application launchers.

        Examples: Desktop icons for Firefox, VLC, GIMP, or your terminal. When you open your application menu, most of the icons you see come from here.

    actions

        What it is: Graphical actions you take inside an application.

        Examples: Cut, copy, paste, save, undo, redo, find, or "add bookmark." These are heavily used in toolbar menus.

    categories

        What it is: Icons representing broad groups of applications, usually seen in the main application menu sidebar.

        Examples: Development, Graphics, Internet, Office, System Settings, or Games.

    devices

        What it is: Physical hardware components or connected peripherals.

        Examples: Hard drives, USB sticks, keyboards, mice, printers, network routers, and audio cards.

    mimetypes

        What it is: File types. "MIME" stands for Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions, but in Linux, it just means file formats.

        Examples: PDF documents, ZIP archives, Python scripts (.py), MP3 audio files, or plain text files.

    places

        What it is: Locations within your file system or network.

        Examples: Your Desktop, Downloads, Documents, and Pictures folders, as well as the Trash bin, Home folder, and network shares.

    status

        What it is: Dynamic icons that reflect the current state of the system or an app, often seen in the top bar or system tray.

        Examples: Battery levels (charging, low), Wi-Fi signal strength, volume levels (muted, full), or chat status (available, busy).

🛠️ Specialized Folders

    animations

        What it is: Sequential images used to create loading animations or progress spinners.

        Examples: A spinning wheel when a webpage is loading, or a moving bar during a file transfer.

    emblems

        What it is: Tiny modifier badges layered on top of regular icons to give extra context.

        Examples: A little padlock icon overlaid on a folder to show it is "read-only," or a small red "X" to show a broken symlink.

    stock

        What it is: Legacy GTK built-in items.

        Note: This is an older convention from GTK2/GTK3 used for standard dialog buttons (like "OK", "Cancel", "Apply"). Modern themes have largely phased this out or merged them into actions, but you still see it for backward compatibility.

📜 The Controller

    index.theme

        What it is: This isn't a directory, but a crucial text configuration file.

        What it does: It acts as the "brain" of the icon theme. It tells the system the name of the theme, its dependencies (inheriting other themes if an icon is missing), and lists every sub-directory alongside their intended sizes (e.g., 16x16, 32x32, scalable) and types (Fixed, Scalable, or Threshold).



🖥️ The panel Directory (The Workspace Layout)

The panel directory contains icons explicitly sized and optimized to sit in your desktop's main panel (like the GNOME top bar, the KDE Plasma panel, or the XFCE panel).

    Why it exists: Icons in a panel need to look perfectly crisp at very small, constrained sizes (usually 16x16, 22x22, or 24x24 pixels) and usually need to be monochrome so they don't visually clutter your screen.

    What you'll find here: System tray icons, volume indicators, network status, battery icons, and clock/calendar icons tailored specifically for panel dimensions.


